body_text.text:
An infrared body temperature screening device that can accurately measure body temperature when inbound and outbound travellers walk through at their usual pace (figure 2
) was established at the two international airports in Taiwan. During the SARS outbreak, passengers with fevers were prohibited from boarding the aeroplane. A hospital near each airport was designated to house, diagnose, and treat any passengers found with fever at the airport. Interestingly, in the summer through fall of 2003, 15 cases of imported dengue and/or malaria were identified at the airports. In part, it is believed that such a fever screening system would serve to deter SARS patients from international travel, and could reduce the international spread of SARS. However, due to the difference in the timing of infectivity in relation to the time of symptom onset (figure 3
), how well this screening device can prevent international spread of infections other than SARS remains to be evaluated.
